         <t:listPerson>
            <t:person sex="2" sameAs="wd:Q148524">
               <t:persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" type="birth">ዘውዲቱ፡</t:persName>
               <t:persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Zawditu</t:persName>
             
                  <t:persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n2" type="baptismal">አስካለ፡ ማርያም፡</t:persName>
               <t:persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n2" type="normalized">ʾAskāla Māryām</t:persName>
                  <t:persName>
                     
                     <t:roleName type="title">nǝgǝśta nagaśtāt</t:roleName>
               </t:persName>
               
               <t:occupation type="ruler">queen</t:occupation>
               <t:birth when="1876">She was born in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2968Ennawa">ʾƎnnawāri</t:placeName>
               </t:birth>
              
               <t:floruit notBefore="1916" notAfter="1930">Zawditu was the empress of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</t:placeName> from <t:date>1916</t:date>to
                  <t:date>1930</t:date>. As a child Zawditu stayed at her father's court under the care of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS2342Bafana">Bafäna</t:persName>, and then his next wife, 
                  <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9345taytuBe">Ṭāytu Bǝṭul</t:persName>.  In <t:date>1882</t:date>, the 6-year-old Zawditu  was married to the 13-year-old 
                  <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS2012Arayas">Arʾaya Śǝllase Yoḥannǝs</t:persName>. But <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS2012Arayas">Arʾaya Śǝllase Yoḥannǝs</t:persName> died in <t:date>1888</t:date>.
                  In <t:date>1889</t:date> Zawditu returned to her father's court. In <t:date>1891</t:date>, she was married to <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4902Gwangul">Gwangul Zägäyye</t:persName>, 
                  but the marriage did not last.
                  In <t:date>1897</t:date> Zawditu married to <t:roleName type="title">daǧǧāzmāč</t:roleName>
                  <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10100WebeAt">Wǝbe Aṭnaf Sägäd</t:persName>. Finally, in <t:date>1900</t:date>, Zawditu  married to 
                  <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4872GugsaWa">Gugsa Wäle</t:persName>, and moved with him to <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2384DabraT">Däbrä Tabor</t:placeName>. 
                  When <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7006Menilek">Mǝnilǝk</t:persName>'s health declined by <t:date>1907/1908</t:date>, Zawditu returned to 
                  <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1216AddisA">ʾAddis ʾAbabā</t:placeName>, together with <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9345taytuBe">Ṭāytu Bǝṭul</t:persName>, nursed her father. 
                  Following the death of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7006Menilek">Mǝnilǝk</t:persName>, <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5620IyasuV">ʾIyāsu</t:persName>
                  put Zawditu under house arrest in 
                  <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3035Fale">Fale</t:placeName>, where her husband had been confined ever since <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9345taytuBe">Ṭāytu Bǝṭul</t:persName> 
                  was forced from power in <t:date>1910</t:date>. Following the overthrown of <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5620IyasuV">ʾIyāsu</t:persName>, 
                  in <t:date>1916</t:date>, Zawditu was asked to ascend the throne. The condition was, however,
                  that she separated from her husband, and thus Zawditu and <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4872GugsaWa">Gugsa Wäle</t:persName> divorced in <t:date>1916</t:date>. 
                  Then, Zawditu ascended to the imperial throne on <t:date>1916-10-02</t:date> and was crowned <t:roleName type="title">nǝgǝśta nagaśtāt</t:roleName>
                  in the <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3292Gannat">Gannata Ṣǝge Giyorgis</t:placeName> on <t:date>1917-02-11</t:date>. But she had no experience in politics and adminsitration.
                  She was believed to be deeply religious, shy but also stubborn. Thus, throughtime, the balance of power gradually shifted in favour of  the then Tafari and later <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5226haylase">Ḫāyla Śǝllāse I</t:persName>, who consequently removed his opponents  and Zawditu 's associates from power. 
                  For the last two years of her life, she was deprived from any political power, even if she still presided formally over the Crown Council.
               </t:floruit>
               <t:death when="1930-11-02">She died of diabetes on <t:date>1930-11-02</t:date>in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1216AddisA">ʾAddis ʾAbabā</t:placeName>. </t:death>
            </t:person>
            
            
         </t:listPerson>
         
      
        
